<H1>Coding Theory</H1>
<H2>(Module M=AALGin <em>Topics in Algebra</em>)</H2>
<H2>Summer Semester 2017</H2>
<H3>Class: Tue 14:15-15:45, Thu 10:15-11:45, SE 30</H3>
<H3>Exercises: Wed 8:30-10:00, SE 30</H3>
  <P>
The practical purpose of coding theory is the transmission of messages
with built-in redundancy, which allows to recognize transmission
errors, or even better, to correct them. A typical approach is the
following: Select a set of words of length <i>n</i> using the
letters <i>0</i> and <i>1</i> such that any two of these words differ
in at least three places. Use these words for transmitting data. If at
most one error occurred in the transmission of a word, then the
correct word can be unambiguously identified. It is, of course,
desirable to have as many words of length <i>n</i> as possible.
Coding theory is about these aspects:
    <ul>
<LI> The construction of codes with best possible parameters. Numerous
methods of number theory, combinatorics, and algebraic geometry are
  used for this purpose.
<LI> Theorems which show the limits of the quality of codes. In the
example above we see immediately that we cannot have more
than <i>2<sup>n</sup>/(n+1)</i> words, since for each code word there
are exactly <i>n+1</i> words differing in at most one position from this
code word, and these sets of <i>n+1</i> words are pairwise
disjoint. With finer or even completely different methods better
  bounds can be shown.
<LI>Algorithms for coding and decoding.
</ul>
<p>
The lecture will focus on the first two aspects.
</p>
